{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17512367","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17512367"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T12:54:32+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T12:54:32+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11885"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11885","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11885"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.16,0.63,0.16,0.04,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4485"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114711"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4485","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4485"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11885"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96714"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"281"},{"type":"tags","id":"1036"},{"type":"tags","id":"1114"},{"type":"tags","id":"2078"},{"type":"tags","id":"2697"},{"type":"tags","id":"9644"},{"type":"tags","id":"10962"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"6578"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6706"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8010"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8967"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15623"},{"type":"contributions","id":"32461"},{"type":"contributions","id":"48273"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114711","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/114711"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 60-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a 30-minute history of persistent, dull chest pain radiating to the left arm. The pain is rated as 8/10 in intensity. He has a medical history of hyperthyroidism and severe iron-deficiency anaemia. His regular medications include carbimazole and oral iron supplements.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears unwell and diaphoretic. His pulse rate is 110/min, blood pressure 150/90 mmHg, respiratory rate 24/min, SpO2 96% on room air, and temperature 37.2\u00b0C. Investigations reveal a haemoglobin of 70 g/L (128-175) and ferritin 9 \u00b5g/L (30-620). An electrocardiogram shows 1 mm ST depression in the chest leads. His troponin level is 10 ng/mL (0-0.04). Urgent coronary angiography shows a right dominant system with no evidence of coronary artery obstruction, TIMI-3 flow in all vessels, and normal left ventricular systolic function and wall motion on invasive ventriculography.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Type 1 myocardial infarction","Type 2 myocardial infarction","Type 3 myocardial infarction","Type 4 myocardial infarction","Type 5 myocardial infarction"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe Universal Definition of Myocardial Infarction classifies myocardial infarctions into five types based on their underlying pathophysiology, clinical context, and management implications. This classification helps guide appropriate treatment strategies and provides prognostic information.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis patient\u0027s presentation is most consistent with a \u003Cstrong\u003EType 2 myocardial infarction (MI)\u003C/strong\u003E. Type 2 MI occurs as a result of an imbalance between myocardial oxygen demand and supply due to non-coronary factors. In this case, the patient has hyperthyroidism and severe iron-deficiency anaemia, both of which can lead to increased myocardial oxygen demand and subsequent Type 2 MI. The electrocardiogram (ECG) reveals ST depression, indicating non-ST elevation myocardial infarction (NSTEMI), and the troponin is significantly elevated, confirming myocardial injury.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EType 1 MI\u003C/strong\u003E is ruled out by the coronary angiography results, which show no evidence of coronary artery obstruction. Type 1 MI is characterised by atherothrombotic coronary artery disease and usually requires revascularisation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EType 3 MI\u003C/strong\u003E refers to cases where cardiac death occurs with symptoms suggestive of myocardial ischaemia and presumed new ischaemic ECG changes or ventricular fibrillation, but death occurs before cardiac biomarkers can be obtained or elevated levels identified, or when MI is detected only at autopsy. This does not fit the patient\u0027s presentation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EType 4 MI\u003C/strong\u003E is associated with percutaneous coronary intervention (PCI), and \u003Cstrong\u003EType 5 MI\u003C/strong\u003E is associated with coronary artery bypass grafting (CABG). Neither of these apply to this patient as he has not undergone these procedures.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EDifferentiating between Type 1 and Type 2 MI is crucial as it impacts treatment. Type 2 MI management focuses on treating the underlying cause (in this case, anaemia and hyperthyroidism) and providing supportive care. Unlike Type 1 MI, Type 2 MI does not typically require coronary revascularisation as there is no coronary obstruction.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Type 2 myocardial infarction occurs due to a supply-demand mismatch, often caused by conditions such as severe anaemia or hyperthyroidism, without coronary artery obstruction.","Differentiating between Type 1 and Type 2 myocardial infarction is crucial as it impacts treatment approach.","The Universal Definition of Myocardial Infarction classifies MIs into five types based on pathophysiology and clinical context."],"references":["Zafari M. What Are The Types Of Myocardial Infarction (MI, Heart Attack), And How Is Each Defined?. In: Medscape.com [online]. 2019. Available at: https://www.medscape.com/answers/155919-15080/what-are-the-types-of-myocardial-infarction-mi-heart-attack-and-how-is-each-defined","Thygesen K, Alpert JS, Jaffe AS, Chaitman BR, Bax JJ, Morrow DA, et al. Fourth Universal Definition of Myocardial Infarction (2018). Circulation. 2018 Nov 13;138(20):e618-e651. doi: 10.1161/CIR.0000000000000617. Available at: https://www.ahajournals.org/doi/10.1161/CIR.0000000000000617"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96714"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11885"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96714","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/96714"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-19T11:02:54+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-19T11:04:17+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4485"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114711"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"2","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","name":"Cardiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":